{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510970"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:36:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:36:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11668"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11668"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.1,0.12,0.03,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4289"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43804"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4289"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11668"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28793"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"126"},{"type":"tags","id":"570"},{"type":"tags","id":"2121"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5785"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6558"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43804"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following a fall on his left arm after slipping in the bathroom.  He has pain in the injured arm, which appears slightly shortened. He has a medical history of hypertension, which has been well controlled medically. His medications include amlodipine. An X-ray is promptly arranged (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely to have been at risk from collateral damage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Radial nerve","Axillary nerve","Musculocutaneous nerve","Ulnar nerve","Median nerve"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has suffered a fracture of the mid-shaft of the humerus secondary to the fall. The radiograph demonstrates a comminuted mid-shaft humeral fracture with medial displacement and anteromedial angulation. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eradial \u003C/strong\u003Enerve runs along the humeral shaft in the radial groove, thus a fracture along the shaft is likely to damage the nerve. Damage to the radial nerve at this level can result in a wrist drop and reduced sensation in the anatomical snuffbox.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eaxillary \u003C/strong\u003Enerve terminates before it reaches the humerus, and thus is not going to be damaged in a mid-shaft fracture of the humerus. If there was a history of high energy trauma and the examination revealed an associated shoulder dislocation, damage to the axillary nerve is worth considering.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emusculocutaneous nerve \u003C/strong\u003Epierces through the coracobrachialis near its point of insertion at the proximal end of the humerus to enter the anterior compartment of the arm, and thus would not be at risk in a mid-shaft humerus fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eulnar nerve\u003C/strong\u003E travels along the medial aspect of the arm, lateral to the brachial and axillary artery, before passing into the posterior compartment halfway down the arm. A history of injury or dislocation at the level of the elbow, rather than the humerus, would be more consistent with an ulnar nerve injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedian nerve \u003C/strong\u003Eruns down the arm with the brachial artery, which does not run in the radial groove. It is the profunda brachii artery, which is a branch of the brachial artery, that runs in the radial groove with the radial nerve.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Radial nerve injury is a common complication of a mid-shaft humerus fracture"],"references":["Silver S, Ledford CC, Vogel KJ, et al. Peripheral Nerve Entrapment and Injury in the Upper Extremity. Am Fam Physician. 2021; :275-85."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28793"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11668"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16014"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16014"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8b3a2ff6-2aaa-4f90-a7aa-25da5310be91.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8b3a2ff6-2aaa-4f90-a7aa-25da5310be91.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":285,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28793"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-27T20:36:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-27T20:36:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4289"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43804"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nul